    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-11-26T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-11-26T05:00:00-05:00" n="1017"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1017">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.922/137: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Siam</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Neville</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bangkok</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-11-26T17:00:00+07:00"
                            >November 26, 1937—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 26—8:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>42. The Minister of Foreign Affairs asked me today whether the United States
                    would be willing to renounce, by an exchange of notes, the right of evocation
                    secured to the United States by articles 2 and 3 of the Protocol annexed to the
                    Treaty of 1920, on the understanding that within 12 months from the date of the
                    notes the Siamese Government would submit to the Assembly of the People’s
                    Representatives an act on the conflict of laws embodying the normal principles
                    of private international law, including especially the law of nationality in
                    matters of personal status, and that pending the promulgation of <pb facs="0897"
                        n="889" xml:id="pg_889"/> such an act, the Siamese courts will continue to
                    apply those principles in all cases concerning American citizens.</p>
                <p>The British have already done this in an exchange of notes accompanying the new
                    treaty, and the Foreign Minister said that the Siamese Government would greatly
                    appreciate similar action by the United States as soon as possible before the
                    Assembly meets on December 10. The exchange of notes would be effective
                    immediately.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Neville</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
